# Finding Memory Leaks and Slow Database Queries

Not every backend slowdown is CPU-bound. Two common sources are memory growth and slow IO. They feel different, require different tools, and leave different clues.

Memory problems usually get worse over time. Database and network problems often show up as high request latency even when CPU usage looks normal.

## What Is a Memory Leak?

A memory leak happens when an application keeps references to data it no longer needs. The garbage collector cannot reclaim that memory because the objects are still reachable.

In production, leaks can cause higher memory usage, longer garbage collection pauses, slower responses, and eventually process restarts or crashes.

## Example Leak

This endpoint stores every large object forever:

```js
const memoryLeakArray = [];

app.get("/memory", (req, res) => {
  const largeObject = {
    data: new Array(100000).fill("leak"),
  };

  memoryLeakArray.push(largeObject);

  res.json({
    message: "Memory allocated",
  });
});
```

The problem is not the allocation itself. The problem is that the global array keeps a reference after the request finishes.

## Using Heap Snapshots

Chrome DevTools can connect to a Node.js process running in inspect mode. In the Memory tab, take a heap snapshot before load, run traffic against the endpoint, then take another snapshot.

Compare the snapshots and look for object types that keep growing. The retaining path is often more useful than the object itself because it shows why the object is still reachable.

## Fixing Unnecessary References

The fix is to remove or limit long-lived references. That may mean deleting cache entries, bounding cache size, avoiding global request storage, cleaning timers, or removing event listeners.

After the fix, repeat the same load test and compare heap snapshots again.

## Slow Database Queries

Database time is one of the most common backend bottlenecks. A request can be slow even if the application code does very little CPU work.

Use database slow query logs and query plans to find expensive queries.

```sql
EXPLAIN ANALYZE
SELECT *
FROM orders
WHERE user_id = 123
ORDER BY created_at DESC;
```

A query plan can reveal full table scans, missing indexes, expensive sorts, or row counts that are much larger than expected.

## Missing Indexes and N+1 Queries

A missing index can make a query slow as data grows. An N+1 query pattern can make one request execute dozens or hundreds of database calls.

Both problems are easy to miss in development because local datasets are small. Profiling with realistic data is important.

## Third-Party API Latency

External services can dominate request time. Track how long each dependency takes and avoid hiding all IO behind a single total request duration.

If a third-party API is slow, consider timeouts, retries with care, caching, background jobs, or returning partial results.

## Logging Request Duration

Even simple structured timing logs can reveal patterns.

```js
app.use((req, res, next) => {
  const start = performance.now();

  res.on("finish", () => {
    const duration = performance.now() - start;

    console.log({
      method: req.method,
      url: req.originalUrl,
      status: res.statusCode,
      duration: `${duration.toFixed(2)}ms`,
    });
  });

  next();
});
```

Once request duration is visible, you can correlate slow endpoints with database logs, external API timing, and heap growth.
